y.stackexchange.com/questions/9358/is-there-a-link-between-autoimmune-diseases-and-x-chromosome-inactivation","last_activity_date":1374500074,"creation_date":1374339044,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is there a link between autoimmune diseases and X-chromosome inactivation?","body":"<p>I was reading about the necessity of <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21519242\" rel=\"nofollow\">niche formations to adequate development of blood progenitors<\/a> and this idea reminded me of the <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/x-chromosome-x-inactivation-323\" rel=\"nofollow\">patchy inactivation of the X chromosome<\/a> which followed that maybe, if some of these pathways passed through X coded proteins, this might make women have different niches, that could account for the seemingly greater occurrence of auto-immune diseases in women. <\/p>\n\n<p>Is there any sense to this idea? Was this ever researched? <\/p>\n","question_id":9358,"tags":["immunology","chromosome","autoimmune"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":9360,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":53,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1374500074},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user3795"},"answers":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user3934"},"score":13,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user3795"},"score":0,"post_id":9372,"edited":false,"creation_date":1374478459,"comment_id":12284,"body":"Excellent information! I am also intrigued as to what caused these bottlenecks.  I used to follow the notion that an eruption of the supervolcano Toba, Indonesia caused an almost extinction bottleneck - but it seems that this is not the case anymore."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1374499607,"creation_date":1374477622,"body":"<p>There is ample genetic evidence for a <a href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12433581\">population bottleneck following the out-of-Africa migration<\/a>. This would account for the reduced genetic diversity found in non-African populations. <\/p>\n\n<p>There is further evidence for an <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v475/n7357/full/nature10231.html\">earlier major bottleneck<\/a> that reduced the human population to around 10,000 individuals.<\/p>\n\n<p>These kinds of studies are typically done now via <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coalescent_theory\">Coalescent theory<\/a> using whole-genome sequences.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>I just found this nice <a href=\"https://whyevolutionistrue.wordpress.com/2011/09/18/how-big-was-the-human-population-bottleneck-not-anything-close-to-2/\">blog post<\/a> summarizing the Nature paper I linked to.<\/p>\n","answer_id":9372,"question_id":9359,"up_vote_count":13,"last_edit_date":1374499607}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9359/is-there-any-evidence-that-humans-have-faced-extinction-before","last_activity_date":1374499607,"creation_date":1374343351,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is there any evidence that humans have faced extinction before?","body":"<p>Have we as a species faced extinction in the past? Resulting in a 'population bottleneck'?  If so, what genetic evidence is there of this occurring?<\/p>\n","question_id":9359,"tags":["human-genetics","extinction"],"score":9,"accepted_answer_id":9372,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":191,"up_vote_count":9},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/65334c6d419e7fa01fe7e356e3fe8ed7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4071,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4071/svetlyo","reputation":18,"display_name":"svetlyo"},"answers":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user3934"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/65334c6d419e7fa01fe7e356e3fe8ed7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4071,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4071/svetlyo","reputation":18,"display_name":"svetlyo"},"score":0,"post_id":9371,"edited":false,"creation_date":1374483234,"comment_id":12290,"body":"Thank you for your answer. I was rather wondering about why should the selective pressure caused by the imperative &quot;avoid being eaten&quot; should be viewed in the light of competing between individuals of the same species and not simply as competition between victim/predator"},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user3934"},"score":0,"post_id":9371,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/65334c6d419e7fa01fe7e356e3fe8ed7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4071,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4071/svetlyo","reputation":18,"display_name":"svetlyo"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1374488330,"comment_id":12293,"body":"I was answering the specific question that you gave at the end. Nevertheless, I added a bunch of text about the saying."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1374488306,"creation_date":1374477009,"body":"<p>The correct answer is, \"it depends.\"  The traits that will be under the strongest selective pressure will be those related to survival in the face of the most common causes of death for that species. If food is abundant but so are predators, then clearly predator evasion will be of supreme importance. If food is scarce, then perhaps metabolism-related traits will be under strong selective pressure. But it's important to remember that just because one selective pressure is stronger doesn't mean that the rest disappear. Thus, the individual's survival is dependent upon really a composite fitness that depends on a countless array of selective pressures, some of which may be larger components than others. The competition between individuals of the same species is really a complex interplay of fitness effects, then.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>As for the maxim about outrunning a cheetah, what it's illustrating is that the gazelles are not competing with the cheetah for survival. They're competing with each other. If you want, you could expand it to say \"...just the other gazelles and the rest of the herbivores in the environment\". If a herd of gazelles and a herd of some slower animal are nearby and a cheetah attacks, one of the individuals from the slower species will probably get caught and all the gazelles will get away. The point is that the gazelles and the cheetahs fill very different niches in the environment, so they don't really compete for the same resources (as a matter of fact, one is the primary resource of the other). <\/p>\n\n<p>When it comes to determining survival, one talks about fitness only within the context of the population (or, if you want, between species directly competing for the same niche). The less fit members of the population do not survive. Thus, the less fit ones that fail to evade the predator are simply doing a worse job evading the predator than the other members of the population. But it's not only the relative fitness that is important. Imagine that a new predator migrates into the environment, for which none of the prey has any evasive adaptation. Even though there may be a relative fitness between them regarding evading this predator, if even the best individual is not good enough to evade it, they would all have an absolute fitness that is too low to ensure survival. Then the saying breaks down, since none of the gazelles can out-run each other with respect to evading this new predator.<\/p>\n\n<p>Of course, this idiom falls apart when you start talking about asocial species, since there aren't any other individuals around to out-run.<\/p>\n","answer_id":9371,"question_id":9365,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1374488306}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9365/competition-with-other-individuals-of-the-same-species-vs-adaptation-pressure-f","last_activity_date":1374488306,"creation_date":1374415970,"answer_count":1,"title":"Competition with other individuals of the same species vs. adaptation pressure from predators","body":"<p>It is often said \"You don't need to outrun the cheetah, just the other gazelles\", thus emphasizing that greater part of the adaptation pressure comes from competing with other individuals of the same species and not directly from predators/parasites (which are seen as more indirect forces similar to the living conditions imposed by the environment (climate, geophysical factors, etc.))<\/p>\n\n<p>My question is:<\/p>\n\n<p>Isn't there a difference between competing with other individuals of the same species for food, habitats (i.e. resources) and competing with them in avoiding being eaten?<\/p>\n","question_id":9365,"tags":["adaptation"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":9371,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":128,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/235bdbadd939d7ec209bcd062eac4e02?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4068,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4068/willummaguire","reputation":118,"display_name":"WillumMaguire"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1374433668,"creation_date":1374433668,"body":"<p>Osteoarthritis results from the gradual degradation of articular cartilage. When the cartilage is damaged extensively, e.g., all the way through the cartilage and into the bone, an inflammatory response ensues in the bone. This often happens when bone is rubbing against bone.<\/p>\n\n<p>One of bone's responses to injury and inflammation is the production of new bone. In this case, the bone, called <a href=\"http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/bone-spurs/DS00627\" rel=\"nofollow\">osteophytes<\/a> or bone spurs, is produced pathologically (i.e., not like the bone laid down normally during growth). Heberden's nodes are the names given to these osteophytes at the distal interphalangeal joints, but the process is basically the same at other joints in the digits, ankle, etc.<\/p>\n","answer_id":9366,"question_id":9362,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9362/enlargement-of-joints-in-osteoarthrosis","last_activity_date":1374433668,"creation_date":1374372122,"answer_count":1,"title":"Enlargement of joints in osteoarthrosis","body":"<p>If osteoarthritis (osteoarthrosis) is a degenerative condition, where the cartilage in joints wears down, what causes the joints to become inflamed? I'm reading through a book called Understanding Disease: Arthritis by Steven Tiger, and it mentions that Heberden's nodes are caused by osteoarthrosis. if things inside the joint are wearing down, why does it get bigger? <\/p>\n","question_id":9362,"tags":["pathology","joints"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":9366,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":94,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b5aaba5a41a84e511931507af7527a36?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3850,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3850/jackopen","reputation":11,"display_name":"jackopen"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8d1f59d2b9f599b976e94b484c2e6e24?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1413,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1413/winerd","reputation":288,"display_name":"winerd","accept_rate":47},"score":0,"post_id":8875,"edited":false,"creation_date":1371834710,"comment_id":11404,"body":"I heard about yogi learning to move their eyes independently, this may be a starting point for research."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hpj4v.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3053,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3053/drosophila","reputation":1073,"display_name":"Drosophila","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":8875,"edited":false,"creation_date":1372096927,"comment_id":11465,"body":"dd3 answered this already, but here&#39;s an idea how to separate your eyes: take a pair of (sun)glasses and put a different sticker on the left and the right piece. Then put them on."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/OxfyD.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3059,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3059/dd3","reputation":2303,"display_name":"dd3","accept_rate":95},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1371836838,"creation_date":1371836482,"body":"<p>First off, I should note that binocular vision is important for depth perception. <\/p>\n\n<p>The phenomenon in which you are interested is called binocular rivalry (distinct images are presented to each eye).  You typically switch between the images, and sometimes, both at once (superimposed; this is called binocular transparency) or an averaged picture (binocular fusion). <\/p>\n\n<p>You can find some good links at the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binocular_rivalry\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia page<\/a>.  The <a href=\"http://www.scholarpedia.org/article/Binocular_rivalry\" rel=\"nofollow\">Scholarpedia page<\/a> is even better.  If you don't find what you're looking for, I think searching for papers on \"binocular rivalry\" will give you the best result. <\/p>\n","answer_id":8882,"question_id":8875,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1371836838}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/8875/eye-brain-mapping","last_activity_date":1374431672,"creation_date":1371789203,"answer_count":1,"title":"Eye Brain Mapping","body":"<p>If our eyes are separated by some kind of full proof barrier/isolation, is it possible that our brain can picture/visualize two different pictures at a time?\nHow the brain will function in this situation?\nwhich are the books to read to understand in depth brain behavior?<\/p>\n\n<p>I tried to isolate my eyes with hands/paper but i am not able to do it.<\/p>\n","question_id":8875,"tags":["neuroscience","brain","eyes"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":84,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1371813247},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3495990e11ded39cbe0ba07c03ab90bb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1086,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1086/lurscher","reputation":210,"display_name":"lurscher"},"closed_date":1413461976,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3cfeec7dfb47b3d98c5edf17295e959b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":81,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/81/poshpaws","reputation":4731,"display_name":"Poshpaws","accept_rate":71},"score":0,"post_id":5471,"edited":false,"creation_date":1355324305,"comment_id":7886,"body":"Check out the answer here <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1242/what-is-the-lowest-pressure-at-which-plants-can-survive\" title=\"what is the lowest pressure at which plants can survive\">biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1242/&hellip;<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3495990e11ded39cbe0ba07c03ab90bb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1086,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1086/lurscher","reputation":210,"display_name":"lurscher"},"score":0,"post_id":5472,"edited":false,"creation_date":1355249807,"comment_id":7875,"body":"i know mars soil will not be up to the task as we know it is highly acidic, 