comment, \"the promoter\" is not a well defined region. Often times \"we\" take the promoter of a gene to be some arbitrary (2-4) kilobytes upstream from the TSS. With more high throughput data coming online (especially from <a href=\"http://genome.ucsc.edu/ENCODE/\" rel=\"nofollow\">ENCODE<\/a>), we are starting to get a better picture of where the <em>functional<\/em> regulatory elements of genes might be.<\/p>\n\n<p>By combining data from several different high-throughput assays across a variety of cell types, the human genome has been <a href=\"http://uswest.ensembl.org/info/docs/funcgen/regulatory_segmentation.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">segmented<\/a> into broad regions of interest. You might start by looking for where the \"Predicted promoter region including transcription start site\" segment is for HBA2.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'd also take a closer look at the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNase-Seq\" rel=\"nofollow\">DNase-seq data<\/a> in this \"promoter region\" across as many cell lines as they have processed for you to look for regions that are differentially occupied in hopes of identifying more precisely which parts in the promoter region might be important for the gene's expression (this would, of course, require you to connect DNAseq data with gene expression (RNA-seq) data).<\/p>\n","answer_id":8829,"question_id":8824,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1371485002}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/8824/information-gene-hba2","last_activity_date":1374078112,"creation_date":1371462074,"answer_count":1,"title":"Information Gene HBA2","body":"<p>Gene : HBA2? hemoglobin alpha 2 (<em>Homo sapiens<\/em>)<\/p>\n\n<p>I don't find any tissues (or organs) in which the expression of this gene is strongest? What is the size of the gene (promoter off) encoding this sequence?<\/p>\n","question_id":8824,"tags":["bioinformatics"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":70,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1371474925},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8ced166484c98a226718d444fc20b7ee?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":3006,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3006/user3006","reputation":26,"display_name":"user3006"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/301d3991a23221c762461fe050c623e5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":192,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/192/steve-lianoglou","reputation":603,"display_name":"Steve Lianoglou"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1359743272,"creation_date":1359743272,"body":"<p>You should ask this question over at <a href=\"http://www.biostars.org\" rel=\"nofollow\">biostars.org<\/a> -- and could use a bit more clarity.<\/p>\n\n<p>Do you actually have RNA-seq data that you want to use to find the exon/splicing structure of an mRNA?<\/p>\n\n<p>First step would be to use a splicing-aware aligner. A few free ones are:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://bioinformatics.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2012/10/25/bioinformatics.bts635.abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\">STAR<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://tophat.cbcb.umd.edu\" rel=\"nofollow\">TopHat<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://research-pub.gene.com/gmap/\" rel=\"nofollow\">GSNAP<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Let us know why that wouldn't do what you want when you re-ask this question over at biostar.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7007,"question_id":7006,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":0,"post_id":7015,"edited":false,"creation_date":1359772244,"comment_id":8592,"body":"I realise that this is not a very biological answer. I did mention splice sites though, four times!"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1374073734,"creation_date":1359771967,"body":"<p>The only information you are missing is a way to identify the splice sites. There are many ways of doing what you need. The simplest, assuming you are sure of the origins of the mRNA, is to use a BLAST flavor, either plain <a href=\"http://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi?PROGRAM=blastn&amp;BLAST_PROGRAMS=megaBlast&amp;PAGE_TYPE=BlastSearch&amp;SHOW_DEFAULTS=on&amp;LINK_LOC=blasthome\" rel=\"nofollow\">BLASTn<\/a> or, even better, <a href=\"http://genome.ucsc.edu/cgi-bin/hgBlat?command=start\" rel=\"nofollow\">BLAT<\/a>, to compare your mRNA sequence to the genome of interest. BLAT really should be all you need if the mRNA comes from the genome you are aligning it to. <\/p>\n\n<p>BLAT however, has no knowledge of splice sites and will simply cut your mRNA so as to maximize local alignment scores. If you need something more sophisticated than BLAT, use a specialized aligner as @SteveLianoglou suggested. These programs include a model of splice sites (both canonical and non) and will align exons correctly. My personal favorite is <a href=\"http://www.ebi.ac.uk/~guy/exonerate/\" rel=\"nofollow\">exonerate<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>Assuming you are using Linux (which you should be if you are planning on doing a lot of this type of analyses), you can install it on a Debian based distribution (such as Ubuntu and its variants) with this command:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-get install exonerate\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Then, to align the mRNA to its gene do:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>exonerate -m est2genome -n 1 mrna.txt dna.txt &gt; out.txt \n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p><code>-m<\/code> is the model that <code>exonerate<\/code> will use to align your two sequences. Since the important thing in your case is to correctly model splice sites, you should use either <code>est2genome<\/code> or, if you are comparing different species, <code>coding2genome<\/code>, or if you have a full length cDNA including UTRs, <code>cdna2genome<\/code>.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p><code>-n 1<\/code> means find the best match only. Assuming you are aligning an mRNA to its coding gene, this is all you are interested in. <\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":7015,"question_id":7006,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1374073734}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7006/how-to-find-exons-in-mrna-computationally","last_activity_date":1374073734,"creation_date":1359740577,"answer_count":2,"title":"How to find Exons in mRNA Computationally","body":"<p>I'm having trouble finding a method to find exons in the original DNA sequence used to create the mRNA, even given the sequence of the mRNA, as I cannot find a way to reliably identify the beginning and end of introns and exons. Is there an algorithm or method that I can use to do this? What information am I missing to be able to find the beginning and end of exons and introns?<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks in advance for answers.<\/p>\n","question_id":7006,"tags":["dna","rna-sequencing","mrna","introns","exons"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":487,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9fc5a15f52c68f1cbcf6c1d47fdca21c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4019,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4019/justin808","reputation":123,"display_name":"Justin808"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/KD6Fx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3952,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3952/oreotrephes","reputation":4267,"display_name":"Oreotrephes","accept_rate":86},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1374018677,"creation_date":1373850316,"body":"<p>That looks like a bit like 