_date":1336402588,"body":"<p>As mentioned in the other answer, red light does not affect the melanopsin receptors in eyes. These receptors not only regulate body rhythm but also <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12808468\" rel=\"nofollow\">regulate the diameters of the eye pupils<\/a>. Once they are stimulated, the eye thinks that there is enough light around and the pupils get smaller to protect the eye against over-exposition, which reduces sensitivity.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2166,"question_id":2075,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1336404461},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/827fb1dcc1982c1e26322c9b48f241dd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1367,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1367/salain","reputation":459,"display_name":"Salain"},"score":11,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe87113ced5f370d038b90a43fd1fe1f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":408,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/408/anixx","reputation":909,"display_name":"Anixx","accept_rate":20},"score":0,"post_id":3471,"edited":false,"creation_date":1347063987,"comment_id":5235,"body":"How can I see blue things by the center of my eye?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/827fb1dcc1982c1e26322c9b48f241dd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1367,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1367/salain","reputation":459,"display_name":"Salain"},"score":0,"post_id":3471,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe87113ced5f370d038b90a43fd1fe1f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":408,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/408/anixx","reputation":909,"display_name":"Anixx","accept_rate":20},"edited":false,"creation_date":1347071953,"comment_id":5238,"body":"You&#39;re essentially a dichromat in the center of the eye, so you are blue-yellow color blind there.  That means you can distinguish blue from any color, except yellow, over a very small region.  You can find a more thorough discussion of the phenomenon by George Wald <a href=\"http://www.opticsinfobase.org/josa/abstract.cfm?id=75312\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe87113ced5f370d038b90a43fd1fe1f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":408,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/408/anixx","reputation":909,"display_name":"Anixx","accept_rate":20},"score":1,"post_id":3471,"edited":false,"creation_date":1347090696,"comment_id":5240,"body":"No, I can distinguish blue from yellow well in the center of my sight."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/827fb1dcc1982c1e26322c9b48f241dd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1367,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1367/salain","reputation":459,"display_name":"Salain"},"score":0,"post_id":3471,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe87113ced5f370d038b90a43fd1fe1f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":408,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/408/anixx","reputation":909,"display_name":"Anixx","accept_rate":20},"edited":false,"creation_date":1347111777,"comment_id":5251,"body":"Center of sight here is defined as 8 minutes of arc, or about 1/8th of a degree of visual angle. It is a very critical angle, though, since it contains your fixation point."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe87113ced5f370d038b90a43fd1fe1f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":408,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/408/anixx","reputation":909,"display_name":"Anixx","accept_rate":20},"score":0,"post_id":3471,"edited":false,"creation_date":1347114297,"comment_id":5253,"body":"I have no color blindness at fixation point."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/827fb1dcc198