ness in µ of normal and rex down-hairs\n\n[Type of Cat][Diameter in um][SE of Mean]\n\nNormal          25.8;   1·32;\n\nEnglish rex     16·2;   0·54;\n\nGerman rex      17·0;   0·50;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n","answer_id":9199,"question_id":9198,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1373399838}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9198/approximately-how-thick-is-a-single-strand-of-cat-domestic-housecat-hair","last_activity_date":1373399838,"creation_date":1373393268,"answer_count":1,"title":"Approximately how thick is a single strand of cat (domestic housecat) hair?","body":"<p>I did a little research to lead me to finding the general range of width for human hair, which is anywhere from around 30µm to 180µm... approximately.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm trying to compare this to the width of cat hair, since I have been told (and it does seem a bit evident) that cat hair is much thinner than human hair in general.<\/p>\n\n<p>I can't seem to find any information on this.  Does anybody have any answers? <\/p>\n\n<p>Note:  I apologize if this isn't the right Stack Exchange forum for this question.  I wasn't sure where to put it, so I did an SE site search for 'cat' and this one seemed to be the most appropriate.<\/p>\n","question_id":9198,"tags":["hair"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":786,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3f4420e2a816a2ad8ecdbab11392278e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3980,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3980/twilight-sparkle","reputation":108,"display_name":"Twilight Sparkle"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/53c30bc1f1ac4e6b256e52b62124da86?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1757,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1757/androidpenguin","reputation":4652,"display_name":"AndroidPenguin","accept_rate":25},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1